  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname \"McCall\" has two capital letters because it follows a traditional naming convention of some Scottish and Irish surnames that include a prefix. In this case, \"Mc\" stands for \"Mac,\" which means \"son of\" in Gaelic. The second part of the name, \"Call,\" is also capitalized to indicate the specific name following the prefix. This pattern is common in surnames with prefixes like \"Mc,\" \"Mac,\" \"O',\" or \"Fitz,\" where both the prefix and the main part of the name are capitalized.",
